Taming Your Advertising Giant

Does it ever feel like your advertising campaign is a giant money swallowing hole? No matter how much you invest to get people’s attention, they never look your way.

What if the problem isn’t *the effort* but *the how* and *the where* of your advertising campaign?

Imagine, for a moment, a contractor who didn’t pay attention to his return on investment, building and selling houses without measuring whether he actually made a profit. What if he didn’t pay attention to whether or not the materials and tools he purchased were worth their price?

Building houses *would* look like a giant hole consuming all of his precious dollars. He wouldn’t know where to cut costs and where to increase his spending.

Of course, we would consider any contractor foolish to do business like this.

Yet it’s easy to do this with our advertisements: throw ads on Facebook, Google, the radio, and local newspaper without implementing any way to measure their effectiveness and return.

Do you know how much revenue each of your advertisements bring in--your Return on Advertising, you might call it? Or are you just trusting your instinct? Do you know whether your advertisements are a massive money drain or a money magnet?

To be as efficient as possible with your advertising dollars, you should use several methods to track your results on every media platform through which you advertise.

**Measuring Your Advertising ROI:**

- **Unique phone numbers:** Although you could measure your Return on Advertising (ROA) several ways, probably the easiest way is to set up a call tracking service, such as *Call Rail* or *CallTrackingMetrics*. By using unique phone numbers in your ads, you can measure exactly how many people see and respond to your ad by tracking which number they call. If you just use your primary phone number across all your ads, you can’t tell if your leads are coming from the ad in the newspaper, radio, Google, or Facebook.

- **Facebook pixels:** If you are advertising online, Facebook pixels allow you to connect your website (including your checkout page) with your Facebook ad. This allows you to measure how many of the people clicking on your ad actually convert to customers.

- **Coupons:** Coupons started as a way to track ROA. By offering unique codes on specific ads that unlock a special discount for the customer, you can track which ads are catching people’s attention. Once you think of coupons like a measuring tool, you can find a myriad of ways to creatively use them.

By measuring your return on advertising, you will know which ads are ineffective and should be cut and which are bringing substantial leads and should be nurtured.

If you do this, you won’t be throwing precious advertising dollars down a drain. Instead, you’ll know exactly where to put your money so you can earn the most revenue through your advertisements.
